    pearls: ["Virchow's triad (stasis, endothelial injury, hypercoagulability) is the foundational concept for understanding DVT pathogenesis -- at least one element is present in virtually every DVT case","A negative D-dimer combined with a low Wells score effectively rules out DVT (high negative predictive value >99%); however, D-dimer should NOT be used alone or in high-probability patients","Proximal DVT (popliteal vein and above) carries significantly higher PE risk than isolated distal (calf) DVT; proximal DVT always requires anticoagulation, while isolated calf DVT management is more controversial","Heparin-induced thrombocytopenia (HIT) is a paradoxical prothrombotic condition -- monitor platelet count every 2-3 days during heparin therapy; a drop >50% from baseline warrants immediate HIT evaluation and heparin cessation","Bed rest is NO LONGER recommended for acute DVT -- early ambulation with compression stockings is safe and reduces post-thrombotic syndrome risk without increasing PE risk","The decision between 3 months versus extended anticoagulation depends on whether the DVT was provoked (transient risk factor) or unprovoked; unprovoked DVT has a 30% recurrence rate at 10 years if anticoagulation is stopped","Cancer-associated thrombosis: DOACs (edoxaban, rivaroxaban) are now preferred over LMWH for most cancer patients, except those with GI or GU malignancies where bleeding risk is higher with DOACs"],
