    pearls: ["The Wells score is a CLINICAL PREDICTION RULE, not a diagnostic test -- it guides the diagnostic pathway by determining pre-test probability, which dictates whether D-dimer testing alone is sufficient or imaging is required","Age-adjusted D-dimer (age × 10 mcg/L for patients >50) maintains sensitivity while significantly improving specificity, reducing false-positive rates and unnecessary imaging in elderly patients by approximately 30%","A negative D-dimer combined with a low clinical probability (Wells <2) has a negative predictive value >99% -- this combination safely excludes DVT without the need for imaging","Whole-leg ultrasound vs proximal CUS: whole-leg scans detect isolated calf DVT but may lead to overtreatment of small distal clots that may never propagate; serial proximal CUS is an acceptable alternative strategy","Compression ultrasonography has sensitivity >95% for proximal DVT but only 50-70% for isolated calf DVT -- this is why serial imaging or whole-leg scanning may be needed when clinical suspicion persists despite negative proximal scan","In pregnancy, D-dimer levels rise physiologically and are frequently elevated in the second and third trimesters, making D-dimer testing unreliable -- proceed directly to compression ultrasonography if DVT is suspected in pregnant patients","The modified Wells score (dichotomized: DVT likely ≥2, unlikely <2) is preferred over the original three-category system (low/moderate/high probability) in current guidelines for its simplicity and equivalent diagnostic accuracy"],
